&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I make the triangle sweep adjustable so I can cover the entire AM or FM
&gt; &gt; &gt; band. Some tuners have different sweep requirements for each band, so
&gt; &gt; &gt; sometimes have to add a pot to adjust the max level for one of the bands.
&gt; &gt; &gt; AM=530 to 1710 Khz and FM 88.5 to 108mhz, but you don&#39;t have to cover the
&gt; &gt; &gt; entire band, all that is required is enough to provide the raw audio bits
&gt; &gt; &gt; the entities use to make their voices.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; A Danish researcher back in the 80s was just &quot;wobbling&quot; between a couple
&gt; &gt; &gt; stations to make contact. His name was Stein and there&#39;s more info on the
&gt; &gt; &gt; German VTF site. Stein also has his sweep circuit there.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; The best sounding systems seem to be the way Steve Hultay makes his, by
&gt; &gt; &gt; adding sweep to a complete radio. see keyportparanormal.com. I take the
&gt; &gt; &gt; tuners out of the radio, and supply my own amplifier and sweep. At
&gt; &gt; present
&gt; &gt; &gt; I&#39;m making a box using a Timex clock radio tuner, the triangle sweep, and
&gt; &gt; &gt; computer sound amplifier and speaker system for the bass response. I just
&gt; &gt; &gt; started this project yesterday. I use Timex model T309T AM/FM/nature
&gt; &gt; sounds
&gt; &gt; &gt; clock radios when I can find them in thrift stores cheap. I found a Timex
&gt; &gt; &gt; model T313T this morning, and hoping it has the seperate tuner board
&gt; &gt; inside,
&gt; &gt; &gt; as the 300 series has so far.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I used to use car stereo tuner modules, but those tend to be too noisy.
&gt; &gt; Box
&gt; &gt; &gt; 13, that Hultay just got back is based on a car tuner. He did a YouTube
&gt; &gt; &gt; video of it.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I&#39;m still pretty much an amateur at this, there are so many variables.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Frank-S
